def simplify_occupation(x):
    
    if x in ['Tradesman - Mechanic', 'Tradesman - Electrician', 'Tradesman - Carpenter', 'Tradesman - Plumber']:
        return 'Tradesman'
    elif x in ['Sales - Retail', 'Sales - Commission']:
        return 'Sales'
    elif x in ['Laborer', 'Construction']:
        return 'Laborer'
    elif x in ['Food Service', 'Waiter/Waitress']:
        return 'Food Service'
    elif x in ['Fireman', 'Police Officer/ Correction Officer', 'Military Enlisted', 'Military Officer']:
        return 'Fireman/Police/Military'
    elif x in ['Student - College Senior', 'Student - College Graduate Student',  'Student - College Sophomore', 'Student - College Junior', 'Student - Community College', 'Student - College Freshman', 'Student - Technical School']:
        return 'Student'
    else:
        return x

loan_data1['OccupationGroup'] = loan_data1['Occupation'].apply(simplify_occupation)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

This is a data set of loan information for various borrowers. It includes the following columns:

  • IncomeRange: The borrower's income range
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • AvailableBankcardCredit: The total available credit via bank card at the time the credit profile was pulled.

  • TotalCreditLinespast7years: Number of credit lines in the past seven years at the time the credit profile was pulled.

  • Occupation: The borrower's occupation

  • LoanStatus: The status of the loan (e.g. Completed, Current, Defaulted, etc.)

  • LoanOriginalAmount: The original loan amount

  • CreditScoreRangeLower: The lower range of the borrower's credit score

  • CreditScoreRangeUpper: The upper range of the borrower's credit score

  • EmploymentStatus: The borrower's employment status (e.g. Self-employed, employed, full-time, etc.)

  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: Whether the borrower is a homeowner or not

  • DebtToIncomeRatio: The borrower's debt to income ratio

  • Investors: The number of investors in the loan

  • BorrowerState: The state in which the borrower resides

  • EmploymentDuration: The duration of the borrower's employment status

  • OccupationGroup: The occupation group of the borrower (e.g. Sales, Skilled Labor, etc.) ### What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

LoanOriginalAmount

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

EmploymentDuration,LoanStatus, Occupation, AvailableBankcardCredit, TotalCreditLinespast7years, BorrowerAPR, BorrowerState , IsBorrowerHomeowner, and IncomeRange may show some trends in relation to the original amount of loans.

def plot_sns_distplot(df,col, hist=True, kde=False,bins=None,xticks=False,
                      xticksrng=None, rotation=90,title=None,color=None,figsizex=10,figsizey=10 ):
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsizex,figsizey))
    sns.distplot(df[col],hist=hist, kde=kde,bins=bins)
    if xticks:
        plt.xticks( xticksrng,rotation=rotation)
    else:
        plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

def plot_sns_countplot(df, x=None, y=None, rotation = 90, order=None,title=None,color=None,figsizex=10,figsizey=10):
    plt.figure(figsize=(figsizex,figsizey))
    sns.countplot(data = df, x=x, y=y, color = color, order=order)
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

In [204]:
def percentage_blocks(df, var):
    """
    Take as input a dataframe and variable, and return a Pandas series with
    approximate percentage values for filling out a waffle plot.
    """
    # compute base quotas
    percentages = 100 * df[var].value_counts() / df.shape[0]
    counts = np.floor(percentages).astype(int) # integer part = minimum quota
    decimal = (percentages - counts).sort_values(ascending = False)

    # add in additional counts to reach 100
    rem = 100 - counts.sum()
    for cat in decimal.index[:rem]:
        counts[cat] += 1

    return counts
In [205]:
waffle_counts = percentage_blocks(loan_data1, 'EmploymentStatus')

prev_count = 0
# for each category,
for cat in range(waffle_counts.shape[0]):
    # get the block indices
    blocks = np.arange(prev_count, prev_count + waffle_counts[cat])
    # and put a block at each index's location
    x = blocks % 10 # use mod operation to get ones digit
    y = blocks // 10 # use floor division to get tens digit
    plt.bar(x = x, height = 0.8, width = 0.8, bottom = y)
    prev_count += waffle_counts[cat]

# aesthetic wrangling
plt.legend(['Employed', 'Full-time', 'Other', 'Self-employed', 'Part-time', 'Retired'], bbox_to_anchor = (1, 0.5), loc = 6)
plt.axis('off');
plt.title('Employment Status Distribution');
plt.axis('square');
plt.show()

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distributions for the following features followed the familiar normal distribution: BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate, TotalCreditLinespast7years, CreditScoreRangeLower, and CreditScoreRangeUpper.

The distributions for the following features had long tails, and log scale transformations were performed on the axis: LoanOriginalAmount, AvailableBankcardCredit, EmploymentStatusDuration, Investors, and DebtToIncomeRatio.

For the Categorical variables:

  • IncomeRange had 7 categories, the 2 most frequent were: \$50,000-74,999, and \\$25,000-49,999
  • BorrowerState: The top 5 states in the number of borrowers are CA,NY, FL, TX, and IL.
  • LoanStatus, with the most of the borrowers falling in either
  • OccupationGroup: other and professional where the largest groups.
  • EmploymentStatus: 'Employed', 'Full-time' are the largest groups of employment.
  • IsBorrowerHomeowner: Slight difference between the two groups with home owners forming 53.14% of borrowers.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The number of investors had a distinct behavior, the peak that has the highest count is at 1 investor, and the remaining range had a somewhat normal distribution with a wide standrd deviation.

In order to make the data more comprhensible, the occupations were grouped according the main major field of work to reduce the number of categories.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

I investigated the relationship between the debt-to-income ratio and the loan original amount using a regplot, but I could not see any clear trend, so I used hist2d instead. I found that most loans had a debt-to-income ratio of around 0.2 and 0.3, and most borrowers had loan amounts between 0 and 10k.

Furthermore, we explored the relationship between loan original amount, employment status duration, and homeownership. We found that the median, Q1, and Q3 of employment duration for homeowners were higher than those for non-homeowners, but the difference was not significant. Homeowners' loan amount median, IQR, and maximum were larger than those of non-homeowners, with a median of about 8k for homeowners and about 6k for non-homeowners. Finally, we plotted a countplot to see the distribution of homeownership among different borrower states. We found that California had the highest number of borrowers, and most borrowers were not homeowners.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I further explored the relationship between loan amounts, income ranges, borrower status, and loan status using various visualization techniques such as bar plots, histograms, facet grids, bar plots, and point plots. The analysis shows that homeowners generally have higher average loan amounts than non-homeowners across all income ranges and five different states. Additionally, borrowers with higher income ranges generally have higher mean loan amounts, and the mean value of completed loans is almost half that of current loans across all income ranges. Furthermore, loan amounts vary by state, with borrowers in California and Texas generally having higher average loan amounts than those in other states.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I find the relation between home ownership status, incomerange and state very interesting. Generally, homeowners borrow higher amounts than non-homeowners. Low income ranges, borrow lower amounts.

Conclusions¶

I can summerize the main findings as follows:

  1. Homeownership status and income range have a significant impact on the loan amounts borrowed. Homeowners generally borrow higher amounts than non-homeowners across all income ranges, and borrowers with higher income ranges generally have higher mean loan amounts.

  2. Loan amounts also vary by state, with borrowers in California and Texas generally having higher average loan amounts than those in other states.

  3. The debt-to-income ratio does not have a clear relationship with the loan original amount, but most loans have a debt-to-income ratio of around 0.2 and 0.3.

  4. The distribution of the number of investors is highly skewed, with a peak at 1 investor and a wide standard deviation. The occupation groups were grouped according to the main field of work to reduce the number of categories and make the data more comprehensible.
